256
00:13:37,720 --> 00:13:39,126
(GROANS)

257
00:13:47,680 --> 00:13:49,041
Lewis!

258
00:13:49,760 --> 00:13:51,086
Lewis!

259
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:57,599
Officer down!
Officer down, 331 Hamilton.

260
00:13:57,600 --> 00:14:01,199
This is Detective Alex Murphy in need
of immediate medical assistance.

262
00:14:01,200 --> 00:14:03,402
331 Hamilton Road.

263
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:05,481
Jack.

264
00:14:06,280 --> 00:14:09,450
Jack, come on.
Jack. Can you hear me?

265
00:14:09,760 --> 00:14:11,928
Jack. Stay with me.

266
00:14:12,680 --> 00:14:13,961
Jack.

267
00:14:14,360 --> 00:14:17,759
<i>KAREN: Alex, you don't
do something like this</i>

268
00:14:17,760 --> 00:14:19,599
unless you bring it to me first.

269
00:14:19,600 --> 00:14:21,119
Vallon's connected.

270
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:25,079
I'm warning you, don't make any
more moves until I vet this.

271
00:14:25,080 --> 00:14:26,879
If officers are supplying
him with guns...

272
00:14:26,880 --> 00:14:29,162
That's up to IAD.

273
00:14:29,400 --> 00:14:31,125
I'll handle it.

274
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:41,442
I don't care how sophisticated
these machines are, Mr. Sellars.

275
00:14:41,480 --> 00:14:46,119
A machine does not know what
it feels like to be human.

276
00:14:46,120 --> 00:14:48,599
It can't understand the
value of human life.

277
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:50,199
Why should it be
allowed to take one?

278
00:14:50,200 --> 00:14:51,319
(APPLAUSE)

279
00:14:51,320 --> 00:14:54,759
To legislate over life and death,

280
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:58,760
we need people who
understand right from wrong.

281
00:14:58,880 --> 00:15:01,159
What do your machines feel?

282
00:15:01,160 --> 00:15:04,759
Well, they feel no anger.
They feel no prejudice.

283
00:15:04,760 --> 00:15:09,522
They feel no fatigue, which makes
them ideal for law enforcement.

284
00:15:10,320 --> 00:15:13,679
Putting these machines
on the streets

285
00:15:13,680 --> 00:15:16,839
will save countless American lives.

286
00:15:16,840 --> 00:15:18,839
- DREYFUS: You're evading the question.
- No, I'm not.

287
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:19,959
DREYFUS:
Yes, you're evading the question.

288
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:23,599
I asked what do these
machines feel?

289
00:15:23,600 --> 00:15:26,644
If one of them killed a child,

290
00:15:27,520 --> 00:15:29,039
what would it feel?

291
00:15:29,040 --> 00:15:30,526
(SIGHS)

292
00:15:32,600 --> 00:15:34,639
- Nothing.
- And that's the problem.

293
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:40,039
That's why 72% of Americans will not
stand for a robot pulling the trigger.

294
00:15:40,040 --> 00:15:42,049
(APPLAUSE)

295
00:15:46,760 --> 00:15:51,124
POPE: America is the world's most
valuable market, and we can't touch it.

296
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:56,679
With a domestic expansion, we'd
clear $600 billion per annum.

297
00:15:56,680 --> 00:16:01,719
In other words, every second that law is
in existence, we are hemorrhaging money.

298
00:16:01,720 --> 00:16:02,879
What do you want me to do?

299
00:16:02,880 --> 00:16:06,399
We've thrown cash at senators at both
sides of the aisle. Nobody's budging.

300
00:16:06,400 --> 00:16:08,479
They don't want to vote
against their constituents.

301
00:16:08,480 --> 00:16:11,679
So unless we sway public
opinion, the battle's lost.

302
00:16:11,680 --> 00:16:13,799
Now, to that effect,

303
00:16:13,800 --> 00:16:18,239
my team have come up with a
pretty aggressive new campaign.

304
00:16:18,240 --> 00:16:20,879
Wow factor off-the-charts.

305
00:16:20,880 --> 00:16:23,924
We need to give Americans
a product they can love.

306
00:16:24,080 --> 00:16:25,919
A figure they can rally behind.

307
00:16:25,920 --> 00:16:29,079
Sir, I have dissected this bill.
There are no loopholes.

308
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:30,839
We can't put a machine
on the streets.

309
00:16:30,840 --> 00:16:32,199
SELLARS: Forget machines.

310
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:33,765
You saw the polls.

311
00:16:34,040 --> 00:16:36,447
Americans don't want a machine.

312
00:16:37,480 --> 00:16:42,125
They want a product
with a conscience.

314
00:16:42,560 --> 00:16:47,690
They want something that knows

316
00:16:48,520 --> 00:16:52,770
what it feels like to be human.

318
00:16:59,120 --> 00:17:01,641
We're gonna put a man
inside a machine.

319
00:17:05,240 --> 00:17:09,159
DR. NORTON: You're not you because
of your legs, your arms, your hands.

320
00:17:09,160 --> 00:17:10,919
You're you because of your brain.

321
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:15,523
It's your brain's capacity to process
information that makes you who you are.

322
00:17:16,720 --> 00:17:21,164
Relax, and just do what
you've always done.

323
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:23,646
(SIGHS)

324
00:17:24,760 --> 00:17:26,799
I've never played with these.

325
00:17:26,800 --> 00:17:31,239
The music doesn't come from your fingers,
Michael, it comes from your mind.

326
00:17:31,240 --> 00:17:33,408
All you have to do is let it out.

327
00:17:34,160 --> 00:17:35,521
Please.

328
00:17:47,320 --> 00:17:49,090
(PLAYING CONCIERTO DE ARANJUEZ)

329
00:18:06,160 --> 00:18:07,850
Oh, my God.

330
00:18:08,240 --> 00:18:09,726
(CHUCKLING)

331
00:18:11,960 --> 00:18:13,764
No, it's okay. Easy.

332
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:15,679
(PLAYS OFF-KEY)

333
00:18:15,680 --> 00:18:18,531
His emotions are peaking. The
readings are getting clouded.

334
00:18:18,640 --> 00:18:19,841
DR. NORTON: It's okay.

335
00:18:20,280 --> 00:18:24,759
Relax. If you get too emotional, it'll
change the chemistry in your brain.

337
00:18:24,760 --> 00:18:26,724
It'll throw the system out.

338
00:18:29,600 --> 00:18:32,326
You're doing great.
Come on.

339
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:36,644
(CONTINUES PLAYING CONCIERTO DE ARANJUEZ)

340
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:48,923
I need emotion to play.

341
00:18:49,560 --> 00:18:51,888
SELLARS: <i>Concierto de
Aranjuez</i>, second movement.

342
00:18:53,040 --> 00:18:54,639
Beautiful piece.

343
00:18:54,640 --> 00:18:57,650
Dennett, when you
have a moment. Thank you.

344
00:18:57,680 --> 00:19:00,759
Now, we agreed on this a
long time ago, Raymond.

345
00:19:00,760 --> 00:19:04,639
I wouldn't be asked to
develop combat applications.

346
00:19:04,640 --> 00:19:07,879
My work here is driven
by its own questions.

347
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:11,519
And your work is brilliant. But
your ideas are being underutilized.

348
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:14,359
Look, I think I found a way

349
00:19:14,360 --> 00:19:18,326
to put real revenue stream
behind your research

350
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:22,083
and save thousands of
lives in the process.

351
00:19:34,720 --> 00:19:37,679
VALLON: You're not keeping up your
end, leaving me exposed like that.

353
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:39,639
Detective Murphy's just
a little impulsive.

354
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:40,799
So put him on the payroll.

355
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:41,959
Why are we talkin' about this?

356
00:19:41,960 --> 00:19:43,599
It won't work. And now
that his partner got hit,

357
00:19:43,600 --> 00:19:45,679
he's never gonna let it go.

358
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:47,719
- What is that?
- Lewis' hospital.

359
00:19:47,720 --> 00:19:51,402
Alex is dropping by this afternoon,
in case you want to send flowers.

361
00:19:53,960 --> 00:19:55,400
(SCOFFS)

362
00:19:55,480 --> 00:19:56,759
Yeah.

363
00:19:56,760 --> 00:19:59,999
I kill a cop, lookin' over my
shoulder the rest of my life.

365
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:01,531
That's not good for business.

366
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:04,607
Who do you think's gonna
be investigating you?

367
00:20:10,600 --> 00:20:13,121
I'm gonna go hard after
Lake and Daniels.

368
00:20:15,120 --> 00:20:17,846
I'm gonna have 'em in bracelets
within a month, man.

369
00:20:19,480 --> 00:20:21,481
MARCUS: Hey, Vallon,
I'm walking up right now.

370
00:20:22,280 --> 00:20:23,891
Cameras off?

371
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:26,241
Clear.

372
00:20:27,360 --> 00:20:31,119
<i>MURPHY: You were right.
We should've had backup.</i>

373
00:20:31,120 --> 00:20:32,685
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

374
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,043
You're not really sleeping, are ya?

375
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:40,285
(CHUCKLES)

376
00:20:40,440 --> 00:20:41,766
Asshole.

377
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:48,961
Sergeant Thomas Ryan, NYPD.
Paralyzed from the waist down.

378
00:20:49,320 --> 00:20:53,359
He has let himself go a
little since the accident.

379
00:20:53,360 --> 00:20:54,679
SELLARS: Pass.

380
00:20:54,680 --> 00:20:56,325
Yeah. Yeah, fair enough.

381
00:20:56,680 --> 00:20:59,326
Officer Alfred Miller, Denver.

382
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:02,919
"Severe Cerebellar..."

383
00:21:02,920 --> 00:21:04,724
Cerebellar ataxia.

384
00:21:04,760 --> 00:21:06,485
That's why you're
the doctor, Doctor.

385
00:21:06,840 --> 00:21:10,599
He scored through the roof
with our urban demos.

386
00:21:10,600 --> 00:21:12,439
Let's keep this one in mind.
I like this guy.

387
00:21:12,440 --> 00:21:15,371
Very good, sir.
I saved the best for last.

388
00:21:16,680 --> 00:21:20,879
I give you Sergeant Jack
Freeman, masculinity incarnate.

389
00:21:20,880 --> 00:21:25,602
Led Pittsburgh SWAT for five years,
now confined to a wheelchair.

391
00:21:27,840 --> 00:21:30,039
I think I can see the appeal.

392
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:31,119
DR. NORTON: No.

393
00:21:31,120 --> 00:21:33,159
(SIGHS) What? Why?

394
00:21:33,160 --> 00:21:36,239
Well, check the psych evaluation.
He's far too unstable.

395
00:21:36,240 --> 00:21:38,249
He's trying to say
that he has a temper.

396
00:21:38,320 --> 00:21:40,879
DR. NORTON: Have you any idea
what we'd be putting him through?

397
00:21:40,880 --> 00:21:44,319
The psychological strain requires
someone emotionally balanced.

398
00:21:44,320 --> 00:21:46,519
We have to be scientific.

399
00:21:46,520 --> 00:21:49,399
I mean, we're not selling a
soft drink here, are we?

400
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:52,331
He's right. Okay. Keep looking.

401
00:21:54,040 --> 00:21:57,119
CLARA: David, what did I say?
Not until you're finished.

402
00:21:57,120 --> 00:21:59,322
- Hey, guys.
- Hi, Dad.

403
00:21:59,480 --> 00:22:02,286
- Hey.
- Hey, little monkey.

404
00:22:06,320 --> 00:22:07,719
How's the game, buddy?

405
00:22:07,720 --> 00:22:10,759
Damon got ejected, but we
got a two-man advantage.

406
00:22:10,760 --> 00:22:13,679
Oh, yeah? That's fantastic.

407
00:22:13,680 --> 00:22:17,164
Hey, D, why don't you head upstairs
and start getting ready for bed.

409
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:19,004
But he just got home.

410
00:22:19,440 --> 00:22:20,959
I'll be up in a second.

411
00:22:20,960 --> 00:22:23,519
Tuck you in, okay? All right?

412
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:24,801
(GRUNTS)

413
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:29,359
- Now give your mom a kiss.
- Good night, baby.

414
00:22:29,360 --> 00:22:30,766
Too slow, boy.

415
00:22:32,600 --> 00:22:34,370
You're just too slow.

416
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:43,399
How's Jack holding up?

417
00:22:43,400 --> 00:22:46,080
They said a week till
he's back on his feet.

418
00:22:46,760 --> 00:22:47,799
It's my fault.

419
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:49,365
We shouldn't even have been there.

420
00:22:51,840 --> 00:22:53,041
Here.

421
00:23:53,840 --> 00:23:55,769
(CAR ALARM BLARING IN DISTANCE)

422
00:23:57,160 --> 00:23:59,119
Oh, shit, I thought I fixed that.

423
00:23:59,120 --> 00:24:00,606
It'll stop.

424
00:24:03,760 --> 00:24:05,371
(MOANING SOFTLY)

425
00:24:06,680 --> 00:24:08,644
It's gonna wake up David.

426
00:24:11,440 --> 00:24:13,290
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

427
00:24:17,040 --> 00:24:18,571
(CLICKING)

428
00:24:28,320 --> 00:24:29,601
(CLICKS)

429
00:24:32,960 --> 00:24:34,605
(UNLOCKS CAR)

430
00:24:52,200 --> 00:24:56,928
<i>DR. NORTON: He suffered 4th degree
burns over 80% of his body.</i>

431
00:24:57,280 --> 00:24:59,926
<i>Lower spine has been severed.</i>

432
00:25:00,680 --> 00:25:02,803
<i>If he survives,</i>

433
00:25:03,360 --> 00:25:07,451
he'll be paralyzed from the waist
down and confined to a wheelchair.

434
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:11,929
Mrs. Murphy,

435
00:25:13,480 --> 00:25:16,001
we don't have to do this.

436
00:25:17,160 --> 00:25:20,409
I need to know everything
before I make a decision.

437
00:25:21,280 --> 00:25:22,811
(SIGHS)

438
00:25:23,480 --> 00:25:25,170
Please continue.

439
00:25:25,960 --> 00:25:31,443
Vestibulocochlear, optical nerves
have been critically damaged.

441
00:25:32,280 --> 00:25:34,608
He'll be blind in one eye.

442
00:25:35,040 --> 00:25:36,685
Most likely deaf.

443
00:25:37,520 --> 00:25:41,439
Frankly, Dr. Norton and the Omni
Foundation are the leaders in this field.

445
00:25:41,440 --> 00:25:45,199
In my opinion, this is the
only chance your husband has.

446
00:25:45,200 --> 00:25:47,801
I'd seriously consider their offer.

447
00:25:50,400 --> 00:25:51,886
I'm sorry, Doctor.

448
00:25:53,280 --> 00:25:54,839
I need time to think.

449
00:25:54,840 --> 00:25:58,965
I'm afraid, Mrs. Murphy, time
is one thing you don't have.

450
00:26:02,800 --> 00:26:05,844
You say you can save him,
but what does that mean?

451
00:26:08,920 --> 00:26:11,088
What kind of life will he have?

452
00:26:13,720 --> 00:26:15,285
(FLY ME TO THE MOON PLAYING)

453
00:26:20,480 --> 00:26:22,967
<i>FRANK SINATRA: (SINGING)
Fly me to the moon</i>

454
00:26:23,400 --> 00:26:27,321
<i>Let me play among the stars</i>

455
00:26:27,840 --> 00:26:30,399
- Thanks.
- Thanks, buddy.

456
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:32,279
You know she's gonna
make me dance again.

457
00:26:32,280 --> 00:26:34,159
Now that I've gotta see.

458
00:26:34,160 --> 00:26:35,279
You don't want to see that.

459
00:26:35,280 --> 00:26:37,079
Here she comes now.

460
00:26:37,080 --> 00:26:38,319
Hold on to that.

461
00:26:38,320 --> 00:26:39,760
Get out there, partner.

462
00:26:41,120 --> 00:26:43,049
Every time.

463
00:26:46,680 --> 00:26:47,879
LEWIS: Get her, boy.

464
00:26:47,880 --> 00:26:49,889
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

465
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:55,399
<i>Fill my heart with song</i>

466
00:26:55,400 --> 00:26:59,969
<i>And let me sing forever more</i>

467
00:27:00,800 --> 00:27:04,079
<i>You are all I long for</i>

468
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:06,239
<i>All I worship...</i>

469
00:27:06,240 --> 00:27:08,279
KIM: Subject is still dreaming.

470
00:27:08,280 --> 00:27:09,559
(CONTINUES SINGING)

471
00:27:09,560 --> 00:27:11,199
He's retrieving memories,

472
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:14,847
trying to make sense of sensorial
stimulation package 37.

473
00:27:15,640 --> 00:27:17,365
Perfect, Kim.

474
00:27:18,680 --> 00:27:20,882
Let's reconnect the spine.

475
00:27:21,680 --> 00:27:23,405
Time to wake him up.

476
00:27:26,840 --> 00:27:29,879
<i>Fill my heart with song</i>

477
00:27:29,880 --> 00:27:33,687
<i>Let me sing forever more</i>

478
00:27:34,840 --> 00:27:38,079
<i>You are all I long for</i>

479
00:27:38,080 --> 00:27:42,604
<i>All I worship and adore</i>

480
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:45,282
<i>In other words</i>

481
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:49,679
<i>Please be true</i>

482
00:27:49,680 --> 00:27:51,405
Excuse me?

483
00:27:51,840 --> 00:27:53,644
What are you doing here?

484
00:27:53,720 --> 00:27:55,239
Baby, where you going?

485
00:27:55,240 --> 00:27:58,639
<i>In other words</i>

486
00:27:58,640 --> 00:27:59,966
Lewis.

487
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:03,921
<i>I love</i>

488
00:28:07,400 --> 00:28:08,931
<i>You</i>

489
00:28:10,440 --> 00:28:13,849
Subject regaining
cognitive functions.

490
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:17,051
What's happening?

491
00:28:19,240 --> 00:28:20,399
Where am I?

492
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:24,999
You were in an explosion,
Alex. You're in a hospital.

493
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:26,281
(STAMMERING)

494
00:28:27,320 --> 00:28:29,999
Where's Clara? My wife.
Where's my wife?

495
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,519
I want you to calm down, Alex.
Listen to me.

496
00:28:32,520 --> 00:28:36,281
You're okay. And your family's fine.
Both your wife and your son.

497
00:28:36,960 --> 00:28:38,605
Who the hell are you?

498
00:28:38,800 --> 00:28:41,765
I'm Dr. Dennett Norton.
I'm treating you.

499
00:28:42,120 --> 00:28:43,526
Heart rate rising.

500
00:28:46,040 --> 00:28:47,651
I can't move.

501
00:28:50,040 --> 00:28:52,759
I can't move.
What the hell is all that?

502
00:28:52,760 --> 00:28:54,079
Visual input unstable.

503
00:28:54,080 --> 00:28:55,559
I want you to relax, Alex.

504
00:28:55,560 --> 00:28:57,039
Subject's dumping too
much epinephrine.

505
00:28:57,040 --> 00:28:58,605
- Should we purge it?
- Not yet.

506
00:28:59,040 --> 00:29:01,242
Unlock vertebrae.

507
00:29:03,480 --> 00:29:05,284
(HISSING)

508
00:29:06,040 --> 00:29:07,571
DR. NORTON: Go ahead, Kim.

509
00:29:07,960 --> 00:29:11,164
Unlock upper, lower extremities.

510
00:29:23,640 --> 00:29:25,879
What kind of suit is this?

511
00:29:25,880 --> 00:29:29,607
It's not a suit, Alex.

512
00:29:31,520 --> 00:29:32,960
It's you.

513
00:29:34,680 --> 00:29:36,519
This was the only option.

514
00:29:36,520 --> 00:29:40,247
We're here, all of us,
to make you whole again.

515
00:29:40,640 --> 00:29:42,079
Full body unlock.

516
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:44,519
I want you to walk now, Alex.

517
00:29:44,520 --> 00:29:46,324
You can do that.

518
00:29:51,560 --> 00:29:53,364
(HEAVY FOOTSTEPS)

519
00:30:09,880 --> 00:30:11,844
This seems so real.

